Modern language models, despite their surface diversity, share a common backbone. Transformers~, gated-attention variants~, recurrent and state-space models~, and memory-based architectures~ differ in how they mix information across tokens, but they are all built from a stack of $L$ identical layers, each combining a token-mixing module with a feed-forward network (FFN). Within this backbone, parameters are distributed uniformly across depth: every layer receives the same allocation, regardless of its position in the stack. As models have scaled by orders of magnitude, this uniformity has remained largely unexamined, a default carried through from the original transformer~.


